{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"b79d2646-7780-4567-9aea-f3de69e2e036","content":"You're on **MSTest 3.8.2**, which supports modern patterns. Here's the recommended approach:\n\n- **Constructor** — for synchronous setup and `TestContext` injection (no more property setter needed).\n- **`[TestInitialize]` as `async Task`** — for asynchronous per-test setup.\n\n```csharp\n[TestClass]\npublic class MyTests\n{\n    private readonly TestContext _testContext;\n    private MyService _service;\n\n    // Sync init + TestContext injection via constructor\n    public MyTests(TestContext testContext)\n    {\n        _testContext = testContext;\n        // synchronous setup here\n    }\n\n    // Async per-test init\n    [TestInitialize]\n    public async Task InitializeAsync()\n    {\n        _service = await MyService.CreateAsync();\n    }\n\n    [TestMethod]\n    public void ExampleTest()\n    {\n        _testContext.WriteLine(\"Running test\");\n        Assert.IsNotNull(_service);\n    }\n\n    // Optional async cleanup\n    [TestCleanup]\n    public async Task CleanupAsync()\n    {\n        await _service.DisposeAsync();\n    }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points for MSTest 3.x:**\n- `TestContext` is **constructor-injected** — the old `public TestContext TestContext { get; set; }` property pattern is legacy.\n- `[TestInitialize]` can return `Task` for async work.\n- Constructor runs first (sync), then `[TestInitialize]` (async) — so you naturally get both.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"44218ba6-71c4-466c-9e10-147efd74e262","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"They're using MSTest 3.8.2 on .NET 9.0. Let me check what the modern MSTest (v3) recommends for initialization patterns.\n\nIn MSTest v3+, the recommended approach is:\n1. **Constructor** for synchronous initialization\n2. `IAsyncInitialization` (or `InitializeAsync`) for async initialization  \n3. **TestContext** can be injected via constructor (MSTest 3.x supports constructor injection of TestContext)\n\nActually, let me be more precise. In MSTest v3:\n- `[TestInitialize]` and `[TestCleanup]` are still supported for per-test init/cleanup\n\n\n- `[ClassInitialize]` and `[ClassCleanup]` handle per-class setup\n- TestContext injection through the constructor is now available, eliminating the need for property setters\n- Async test initialization is supported by making `[TestInitialize]` return a `Task`\n- You can layer both constructor injection for synchronous setup and `[TestInitialize]` for asynchronous operations","outputTokens":799,"requestId":"7C23:21DC3D:27A2309:2C02E1F:69F948CA"},"id":"a874e659-5b1b-47d0-a48c-1b14652f40b5","timestamp":"2026-05-05T01:33:14.911Z","parentId":"eba21a4b-a8a2-45ec-9310-72959de2ee79"}
